##With China's outbreak under control, why is there so much infection around the world?

I-CAIJING

If all goes well, the IMF believes, China's economy could begin to return to normal in the second quarter. The number of confirmed cases in individual countries and regions and the number of countries and regions with the first new cases of coronavirus infection are increasing? Or has the epidemic reached a new tipping point?

A worker takes the temperature of a passenger at the Al Najaf International Airport in Iran on February 21,2020. Figure / Fachen

By Jin Yan, CAIJING correspondent in Washington

Editor | Susie

The number of newly diagnosed cases in China has been falling in recent days, despite the growing number of cases, after more than a month of prevention and control since the outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia in Hubei Province on January 20, the number of cured and discharged cases continued to increase, and the spread of the epidemic was initially contained. Outside China, South Korea, Japan, Italy and other places have recently seen a number of cluster infections, a rapid increase in the number of confirmed cases, the situation of the spread of the epidemic in the world caused great concern.

Meanwhile, the recent strength of stock markets from the US to China suggests the financial impact of the outbreak has been limited. Looking ahead to first-quarter and full-year growth, the International Monetary Fund and a number of investment agencies have recently released their latest forecasts, most of which point to a return to normal from the second quarter.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The IMF forecasts 5.6 per cent growth this year

On February 21, the Politburo of the Communist Party of China convened a meeting to study the prevention and control of the new coronavirus epidemic, and to coordinate the prevention and control of the epidemic as well as economic and social development. General Secretary of the Communist Party of China chaired the meeting. The meeting noted that the current epidemic situation has been initially contained, prevention and control efforts have achieved phased results, the number of newly confirmed cases and suspected cases nationwide has shown an overall downward trend, and the number of cured and discharged patients has increased rapidly, in particular, the number of new cases dropped sharply in provinces outside Hubei. At the same time, we should be clear that the turning point of the national epidemic development has not yet arrived, the situation in Hubei Province and Wuhan is still grim and complex.

A total of 397 new cases were reported in 31 provinces, autonomous regions, municipalities and the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps as of 2400 hours on February 21, according to figures from the NHRC, there were 109 new deaths, 106 in Hubei, 1 in Hebei, 1 in Shanghai and 1 in Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, and 1,361 new suspected cases. It is worth noting that 397 new cases were confirmed that day, down sharply from 889 the previous day.

On February 22nd CRISTALINA Georgieva, managing director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) , made a statement at a meeting of G20 finance ministers and central bank governors in Riyadh, "The Chinese authorities are using crisis management measures, liquidity supplies, fiscal measures and financial support to try to mitigate the negative impact of the epidemic on the economy. "

The IMF forecast in January that global growth would accelerate from 2.9 per cent last year to 3.3 per cent this year. Since then, the COVID-19 outbreak -- a global public health emergency -- has disrupted economic activity in China. The current baseline scenario for the IMF forecast assumes that China has implemented the measures announced and that the economy will return to normal in the second quarter. As a result, the impact on the global economy in the future is likely to be smaller and shorter in duration. In this scenario, China's economy would grow by 5.6% in 2020. That was 0.4 percentage points lower than in January's World Economic Outlook Update. Global growth will slow by about 0.1 percentage points.

The IMF acknowledged that the complexity of the virus's spread was still being studied and that the uncertainties were too great to make reliable predictions. Many scenarios could occur, depending on how quickly the virus is contained and how quickly China and other affected economies return to normal.

Business activity in the COVID-19 fell to its lowest level in more than six years in February as companies fretted about the effects of the epidemic and fears that the outbreak would slow global growth, survey data showed.

Alicia Garcia-Herrero, Chief asia-pacific economist at Natixis, told Caijing that Chinese companies faced new obstacles to resuming production and that measures had led to some companies returning to work very slowly. Some are low even at start-up productivity, and thus have some impact on the supply chain. Although tariffs also have an impact on supply chains in the case of trade frictions between China and the United States, this coronavirus outbreak has an even greater impact on the supply chain because of the uncertainty it creates, both in terms of duration and scale, and tariffs are not only publicly announced, but on a measurable scale.

China's ambassador to Saudi Arabia told a meeting of G20 finance ministers and central bank governors that despite the outbreak, China could still achieve this year's economic growth target.

The World Health Organization believes that strong and coordinated measures can still control the spread of the virus in China and around the world and prevent the continuation of the human tragedy. But the IMF does not rule out a more severe scenario -- a virus that lasts longer, spreads more globally and has a more lasting impact on economic growth.

Behind the rise of outbreaks in many parts of the world

While the total number of cases outside China is relatively small, there are worrying signs in recent days of a surge in confirmed cases in individual countries and an increase in the number of countries with the first new cases of coronavirus infection. Is the source of infection increasingly difficult to identify in newly infected populations? Or is the epidemic reaching some kind of tipping point?

Who director-general Tan Desai said that, "The window of opportunity is narrowing, so we need to act quickly before it closes completely. In tandset's view, the epidemic could go in any direction, avoid any serious crisis if done right, but face a serious problem if the opportunity is wasted.

South Korea recorded 20 new cases on Feb. 19,53 on Feb. 20 and 100 on Feb. 21. A total of 556 new cases were confirmed and there was a fourth death case of new coronary pneumonia in South Korea as of 9:00 am Wednesday. Cases of the new coronavirus jumped 18-fold in a week. KBR reported that on February 22, South Korea, Gangwon Province, Sejong the Great and Ulsan City, new coronary pneumonia (COVID-19) confirmed cases. At this point, South Korea 17 wide-area city road cases, the epidemic was the trend of full spread.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A worker in protective clothing transports a suspected case of new crown pneumonia in Taegu, South Korea, on February 21,2020. FIGURE / method new

Similarly, new cases are multiplying in a single day in Italy, also in Europe. Italy has confirmed a total of 79 cases of new coronavirus pneumonia infection, 1 cured discharged from hospital, 2 deaths. The cases are concentrated in the northern regions of Lombardy  LombardiaReg. And Veneto, which has become Europe's worst affected country.

The number of confirmed cases reported in Italy increased from three to 17 in one day. The country has ordered mandatory isolation of anyone who has come into contact with a patient who tests positive for the virus. Twelve towns were blockaded and more than 50,000 residents were asked to remain in their homes. It is believed to have originated from an infection cluster in a local hospital and coffee shop. Schools, churches, stadiums and other public facilities were closed on February 21 in Codogno, more than 60 kilometers from Milan, after the first death from new coronavirus pneumonia, AFP reported.

The World Health Organization has made it clear that it is worried that the recent surge in new coronavirus infections in Iran may be a sign of a worsening of the epidemic. Iran has reported 18 cases of infection in the past two days, including at least five deaths. The new outbreak began in the religious city of Qom, but it is not clear how. To make matters worse, infected people from Iran have been found in Lebanon and Canada. "Our biggest concern remains the possibility of coronavirus transmission in countries with weak health systems in 2019, " Tandsey said. To that end, World Health Organization launched the strategic preparedness and Response Plan, which raises $675 million to provide special support to the most vulnerable countries."

The aggravation of the epidemic in some countries is mainly due to cluster infection.

Virologists have two possible explanations for aggregated transmission. One possibility is that a "hyper-spreader" -- a person who exhibits a higher tendency to shed germs than others -- is called a "Florida virus" -- is spreading it to a large group of people. Some superspreaders have no symptoms of their own and go out feeling not sick, or they meet a group of people with low resistance.

In South Korea, for example, about 230 of the confirmed cases were directly linked to a branch of the new World Jesus Church in Taegu, possibly infected by a woman in her 60s who attended two services, she later tested positive for the virus. South Korean officials are now investigating whether church-goers are linked to a surge in hospital infections in Cheongdo County. So far, more than 110 people have been diagnosed at the county hospital, most of whom live in the hospital's psychiatric ward. South Korea's deputy health and Welfare Minister, Kim Gang-lip, said the country's new coronavirus outbreak has entered a serious new phase, but he remained cautiously optimistic.

Another interpretation of agglomerative transmission is that people can infect viruses from contaminated surfaces in unrelated ways. It is not clear how long the new coronavirus will survive on the surface, but studies of other such viruses have found that their activity lasts a week or more.

While the worst is yet to come, cases have surged in Iran and South Korea, with Lebanon and Israel in the Middle East reporting their first confirmed cases of COVID-19 infection Sunday. Who director-general Tan Desai has called for a swift international response to contain the spread of the disease.
